TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Informal Look at the Principle of Optimality
AU  - Porteus, Evan
Y1  - 1975/07/01
PY  - 1975
DA  - 1975/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.21.11.1346
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.21.11.1346
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1346
EP  - 1348
VL  - 21
IS  - 11
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The Principle of Optimality is examined informally in the context of discounted Markov decision processes. Our purpose is to illustrate that one should be invoking the optimality equations and/or the optimality criterion, rather than the Principle of Optimality in analyzing dynamic models. A counterexample to one interpretation of the Principle is given. It involves a foolish action at the second stage from a state that can be reached, but with probability zero. Redefining optimality as in Hinderer [Hinderer, K. 1970. Foundations of Non-stationary Dynamic Programming with Discrete Time Parameter. Springer-Verlag, New York.], restores the Principle, at the cost of a weaker notion of optimality.
AB  - The Principle of Optimality is examined informally in the context of discounted Markov decision processes. Our purpose is to illustrate that one should be invoking the optimality equations and/or the optimality criterion, rather than the Principle of Optimality in analyzing dynamic models. A counterexample to one interpretation of the Principle is given. It involves a foolish action at the second stage from a state that can be reached, but with probability zero. Redefining optimality as in Hinderer [Hinderer, K. 1970. Foundations of Non-stationary Dynamic Programming with Discrete Time Parameter. Springer-Verlag, New York.], restores the Principle, at the cost of a weaker notion of optimality.
